[23:16] <geekosaur> I see a misunderstanding here, that {$x} in perl 6 is somehow the same as shell's ${x}. it's not.

[23:17] <geekosaur> in a double quoted string, { some expression } interpolates the result of that expression.

[23:17] <geekosaur> m: "it's { sin 5 }".say

[23:17] <camelia> rakudo-moar e9351cbaa: OUTPUT: ¬´it's -0.9589242746631385‚ê§¬ª

[23:19] <raschipi> ToddAndMargo: do you see the difference? {...} in Perl6 works like in C, ity creates a block.

[23:21] <geekosaur> or a hash, in some contexts; or as a postcircumfix, associative indexing (e.g. %foo{$key})

